Following the coining of the term ‘hadal’ by the leader of the 

Galathea
Expedition (
Bruun, 1956
)

, another member of the expedition published the first concept of a ‘hadal community’ (

). 
Amphipoda
was listed as a dominant hadal group, alongside several others, namely holothurians, isopods, and polychaetes. The number of species known was 20–25, with 56% estimated to be endemic (

). Just ten years later, 

re-evaluated these figures based on many other records supplied by 

following the 
Vitjaz
expeditions. He reported 17 hadal amphipod species, of which 14 (82.4%) were endemic, and declared that the amphipods were in the ‘five significant abyssal-hadal groups’ as defined by a high percentage of hadal species (alongside echinoids, polychaetes, bivalves, and holothurians). All these studies were based largely on ‘rather ponderous samplers’ (

), such as bottom trawling and sediment grabs and dredges, which are now known not to be the optimum method in recovering highly mobile species, such as scavenging amphipods (

).

Following the Danish and former Soviet Union expeditions from the late 1950s to the 70s, trawling at hadal depths largely ceased. The turn of the century saw the free-fall camera and trap methods adopted more commonly for hadal research (

), although some modern trawling expeditions have occurred specifically at the Kuril-Kamchatka Trench (Northwest Pacific) (

). This led to a sudden increase in the sampling of, and research, into the diversity and community structure of hadal amphipods (e.g., 

